Binom test

Statistical measure for testing that vector have certain probability if success.

H0 - distribution matches set probability H1 - distribution diverge set probability

p-value <= 0.05 we can reject HO, we cannot reject H1

NUMBER_OF_SUC <- 1
NUMBER_OF_TRIALS <- 10
DESIRED_PROBABILTY <- 0.5 #### (from 0 to 1)


binom.test(NUMBER_OF_SUC, NUMBER_OF_TRIALS, DESIRED_PROBABILTY)
## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  NUMBER_OF_SUC and NUMBER_OF_TRIALS
## number of successes = 1, number of trials = 10, p-value = 0.02148
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.002528579 0.445016117
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.1

T-test

Statistical measure for testing if means of two vector significantly different.

H0 - Two mean are not really different H1 - Two mean are different

p-value <= 0.05 we can reject HO, we cannot reject H1

?t.test
a <- rnorm(100, mean = 10, sd = 10)
b <- rnorm(100, mean = 10, sd = 10)

t.test(a, b)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  a and b
## t = 1.087, df = 196.35, p-value = 0.2784
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.260333  4.356010
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 10.160177  8.612338

Lets try real example!!

## Easy way to write formula
t.test(df$bmi ~ df$sex) 
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  df$bmi by df$sex
## t = -1.697, df = 1336, p-value = 0.08992
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.21895043  0.08819153
## sample estimates:
## mean in group female   mean in group male 
##             30.37775             30.94313

How it works? Lets replicate it.

a <- df %>% 
  filter(sex == 'male') %>% 
  pull(bmi)

b <- df %>% 
  filter(sex == 'female') %>% 
  pull(bmi)

t.test(a, b)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  a and b
## t = 1.697, df = 1336, p-value = 0.08992
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.08819153  1.21895043
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  30.94313  30.37775

Absolutely the same.

ANOVA

Why do we need it? Guess we to check H1 about region influence?

What Analysis Of Variance is?

Statistical measure for testing if means of two or more (sic!) vector significantly different.

H0 - Means are not really different H1 - Means are different

p-value <= 0.05 we can reject HO, we cannot reject H1

aov(df$charges~df$region)
## Call:
##    aov(formula = df$charges ~ df$region)
## 
## Terms:
##                    df$region    Residuals
## Sum of Squares    1300759681 194773461887
## Deg. of Freedom            3         1334
## 
## Residual standard error: 12083.34
## Estimated effects may be unbalanced

Chi-square

Statistical measure for testing if means of two or more (sic!) vector significantly different.

H0 - Distribution in matrix is uniform H1 - Distribution in matrix is NOT (!sic) uniform

df %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_wider(id_cols = smoker, # what would be in rows
                     names_from = sex, # what columns would be split
                     values_from = charges, # what values will be filled
                     values_fn = mean) # what function will applied
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   smoker female   male
##   <chr>   <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 yes    30679. 33042.
## 2 no      8762.  8087.

Correlations

Do not returns p-value! Its just a measure just to detect alike vectors.

Value should be above 0.6 if sample is big, but it could be less in small samples.

Note! Very important! Matrix can be changed if you add here highly correlrated vector - probably some correlation would vanish, while some wont.

df %>% 
  select(is.numeric) %>% 
  cor
